<!DOCTYPE html>
<%#Rails 3 uses HTML5 by default (as indicated by the doctype <!DOCTYPE html>);  
%>
<html>
  <head>
    <title><%= full_title(yield(:title)) %></title>
    <%= stylesheet_link_tag    "application", media: "all" %>
    <%= javascript_include_tag "application" %>

<%# meta tags prevent cross-ste request forgery %>
<%# authenticity tokens get inserted with every request %>
    <%= csrf_meta_tags %>
    <%= render 'layouts/shim' %>    
  </head>
  <body>
    <%= render 'layouts/header' %>
    <div class="container">
      <%#  
      Before submitting a valid registration in a browser, weâ€™re going to add a bit of polish common in web applications: a message that appears on the subsequent page (in this case, welcoming our new user to the application) and then disappears upon visiting a second page or on page reload. The Rails way to accomplish this is to use a special variable called the flash, which operates like flash memory in that it stores its data temporarily. 
      %>
      <% flash.each do |key, value| %>

        <%# note use of div as a symbol below,  :div    %>  
        <%= content_tag(:div, value, class: "alert alert-#{key}") %>
        <%# 
        NOTE the use of content_tag above, which
        replaces the line below to make things easier to read....from  Listing 7.33.  

        NOTE inserted space between % and > combos below to extend this comment
         <div class="alert alert-<%= key % >"><%= value % ></div>
        end comment ....  %>

      <% end %>

      <%= yield %>
      <%= render 'layouts/footer' %>
      <%= debug(params) if Rails.env.development? %>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
